narratives.question_text: How would you summarize ECON 110 05 for a fellow student? Would you recommend ECON 110 05 to another student? Why or why not?
comments: I would totally recommend this class to another student if they are into the material or want to get into the material. Also, I would recommend this class just because of Professor Walsh because he is outstanding.
Take this class! It's a great survey of Early Modern Drama, with a professor who keeps the conversation interesting and informative.

This is an interesting class, covering a lot of infrequently read plays from Shakespeare's contemporaries, as well as Shakespeare plays. I recommend Brian Walsh-- he is a really nice professor and really likes the subject matter.

I would recommend this class for Shakespeare enthusiasts. It's very interesting to put Shakespeare into a more historical context and consider him alongside other playwrights. I would say two-thirds or so of the plays we read were by authors other than Shakespeare, so if you are looking for a pure Shakespeare class, this may not be the class for you. That said, this was one of the most interesting seminars I've taken at Yale.
Absolutely take it! It's a great chance to study Shakespeare's contemporaries (and Shakespeare too, of course). Brian Walsh is great, and discussions were interesting and fun.
This is a wonderful class. I highly recommend this seminar and Walsh's classes in general.
I would recommend this class to anyone who enjoys drama, and wants to learn more about playwrights outside of the Bard.

I would absolutely recommend this class, even if you're not a senior English major. It's a really fun discussion seminar. You read a bunch of interesting plays and write a few papers. The workload isn't too bad, though keeping up with the readings (a play a week, roughly) can be a little rough. But the focus of the class is really interesting, and Professor Walsh is wonderful.
